The Udaipur Urban Control Area (UUCA) has a population of 0.8 million (2016) and envelops an area of 348 km2; tourism forms the economic base of Udaipur, a city with rich cultural and built heritage. In 2019, 1.2 million tourists visited Udaipur, according to the Rajasthan Tourism Board. Udaipur is traditionally a compact city with a dense, ring-radial road network. The latter is, however, now rapidly expanding along two highways, which has created high travel demand (Figure-3
                        ). Udaipur has a small urban centre; 75% of the population resides within 18% of the total area. The traffic composition of Udaipur is predominantly comprised of 2Ws; such transport also serves high-income groups. Despite their poor quality, there is reliance on intermediate public transport and non-motorised transport. Overarching transport trends for both cities are listed in Table 2
                        .
